manic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":39,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":41,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":55,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":57,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Walsheer was born in 1530, in Pitminster, Somerset, England, his father, William Walsheer, was 83 and his mother, Elizabeth Williams, was 30. He married Elizabeth Walsyngham in 1550, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1595, in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1530–1595":"1530–1595","1520–1596":"1520–1596","1533–1596":"1533–1596","1551–1607":"1551–1607","1447–1533":"1447–1533","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1550":"1550","19 January 1560":"19. jaanuar 1560","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1 January 1533":"1. jaanuar 1533","1447":"1447","1500":"1500","1533":"1533","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1595":"1595","1551":"1551","30 August 1551":"30. august 1551","1607":"1607","1549":"1549","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whaddon, Aylesbury Vale, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aylesbury Vale, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pitm